title: For Sale/Trade:  XDm 5.25 .45 ACP w/PRP Trigger and Patriot Magwell
postcontent:
I have a Springfield XDm 5.25 chambered in .45ACP, with a PRP Trigger Kit installed and a Patriot Magwell, that I would like to trade.  

From the Powder River Precision website about the trigger kit (plus I am including the stock trigger):
"This Drop in Trigger Kit fits all XDM pistols including the new XDM5.25". The kit contains our famous striker safety lever, to remove the long trigger pre-travel on the XDM trigger. Reduced power: trigger spring, sear spring, striker safety spring and striker spring, to lower the pull weight. Our trigger is made of tough light weight polymer that helps speed up the reset. It also has an integral over travel stop on the back of the trigger. Using this method of over travel stop removes added stress on the trigger bar that are present with any of the other over travel stop methods. This trigger is a Springfield Armory OEM part available on production XD and XDM pistols from the factory (see APPENDIX D4 — 21.6 Production Division Rules). When installed correctly, the kit will give you a short crisp trigger pull (about 3.5-4.5lbs) with a fast reset and shorten the total trigger pull length. Fits all XDMs."  [url]http://shop.powderriverprecision.net/product.sc?productId=73&categoryId=3[/url]

From the Pistol Gear website about the Patriot Magwell:
"PistolGear is proud to offer the first IDPA legal magwell to the XDm marketplace. Tweaking our design for the benefit of an affective product that will fit the IDPA box, this magwell will make your ESP machine rock! The PistolGear "Operator" magwell for the XDm doubles the width of the frame funnel for the benefit of smoother tactical reloads. The magwells locks onto the frame in two locations making it rigid. The magwell is held in place by a threaded pin that replaces the factory grip insert pin, making installation easy and non-permanent. YOU DO NOT EPOXY THIS PRODUCT TO YOUR FRAME. 

This set up new would cost you as follows:
Springfield XDm 5.25 out the door price from SSP (pistol, shipping, sales tax) - $754
PRP Drop in Trigger Kit - $125
Patriot Magwell - $85
Total Out The Door would be $954 if buying new, I don't expect that at all.

As for what I am looking for, I would like to trade a nice stainless (would consider other than stainless) 1911 in the "Commander" size.  i.e. Colt Commander, Kimber Pro, Springfield Champion, Sig Sauer, etc... I would also be interested if somebody just happens to have an upper chambered in 300 AAC Blackout but I doubt that will happen. See list below.  I might consider other offers so just let me know what you have.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 1917 Revolver
postcontent:
This is maybe one of the most famous Smith & Wesson Models made. 
It was developed during WWI as an interim sidearm when the Army could not produce enough 1911s. They contracted with S&W and then Colt to produce a .45 ACP caliber handgun to use as a fill in until there were enough 1911s to go around.
What resulted was the Model 1917. It proved so popular that it continued production after the war and exported to many different countries.
This particular Model 1917 was produced in 1937 in Springfield, Mass. to fulfill a contract with Brazil.
Many of these Brazilian Contract 1917/1937 revolvers were reimported after Brazil changed to the 9MM.
I purchased this one in 1991 and have treasured it for its history and great shooting ability.
The finish shows a lot of holster wear, it was carried a lot and shot little. The interior workings are in very good shape and the bore is bright.
I have fired it and it is accurate and easy to shoot. It has a light, smooth trigger pull and hits where you point it.
It uses full moon clips and there are 6 included.
There is also a set of Pachmyer Presentation grips included. These make it a joy to shoot.
Since I retired I have been selling my stuff and this is the last of it. I held onto it as long as I could. It is time for it to have a new home.
More pictures can be seen here; http://photobucket.com/Model_1917

I am asking $650.00 OBO.

title: For Sale:  VFC AKS74U w/ custom wood ergonomic grip
location: Palm Harbor- Pinellas Area., Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
I have for sale a very lightly used VFC AKS74UN Deluxe version with re-tuned gear box. Story of this gun, purchased and used at a few games by a comrade until he joined the army, then it sat on his shelf for about a year until I became the owner. It is the deluxe version, meaning it has a unique serial number and.... that's it. These aren't made anymore and retailed at $475.00
The gun also has a very unique grip that is no longer made as well... It is strange at first but when you realize not to hold it like a normal vertical grip you love 

Price $250 (Comes with 1 midcap, but I warn it is awful, I'm in the process of replacing all my warn out mags.) Can ship, meet in Pinellas area or Amerika2


Internal work. Sitting so long weakened the spring and dried the piston seal. Replaced the spring with a pretty pink one to return it's power and give it some class. Replaced the aluminum piston head with a Systema aluminum piston head, corrected VFC's awful shim job, replaced spring guide with a ball bearing spring guide, put aluminum cylinder head and nozzle on for shits and giggles. The gun shoots consistently around 350 FPS with a .20 BB, recommend 9.6v stick battery. 

http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/vfcgearbox.jpg - Gear box nude pix.

Externals only 2 things to mention as damage, one would be the weld marks on the stock from when it was reinforced, my previous VFC had the stock break on the factory welds, so we reinforced this one right away. Also there are scratch marks on the flash hider as it was on there quite tight. 

http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00083.jpg
http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00082.jpg
http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00081.jpg - stock weld marks
http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00088.jpg Flash hider close up

This gun is incredibly durable, my [u]other[/u] VFC AKS74U has survived 5-6 years of being dropped, thrown, submerged in water, tossed through windows, used as a battering ram... and many other acts of civil disobedience. 
You figure all that abuse would tear a gun up, but I have yet to find a way to destroy a VFC AK. 
http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00094.jpg
Bottom one is the one for sale, the top one is what to expect after 5 years of abuse. The more you abuse it the better it looks and the body never breaks.

Picture dump!


http://i4.photobucket.com/albums/y130/Pyro_Ducky/DSC00077.jpg

The PLR-22 pistol is chambered for the popular and economical .22 Long Rifle cartridge (.22LR). It is based on the 5.56mm NATO chambered PLR-16 pistol and shares many parts including the grip and front and rear sights. The PLR-22 is not a simple conversion kit, it is a standalone firearm chambered for the .22LR and is designed for target shooting, plinking, or small game hunting. The PLR-22 and SU-22 operate by blowback action and have a 4140 steel bolt that rides on steel guide rails inside the polymer receiver. The ejector is attached to one of the guide rails and the recoil spring is located above the barrel. The cross-bolt safety and magazine release operate identically to the PLR-16 and SU-16.

title: For Sale:  Hungarian Side Folding AK AMD-65 w/ Extras
postcontent:
This is an AK and it is different than most AK's because most AK's are imported as parts kits into the country and then assembled in the USA on imported or US receivers...this rifle was imported as an FEG ( Hungarian made) rifle with a 10 round single stack mag (how they got around importation as you cannot import a rifle that has in excess of a 10 round mag).  Once imported, it was converted to take 30 round mags thus NOT compromising the integrity of the foreign (and better built) rifle.  I have a ton (count them) of ten round stripper clips of High End American ammo as well as some Russian ammo (in the mags, each half full so they won't fully compress the springs in the mags).
